ce:section.ce:para:
Battery degradation is the result of electrochemical ageing and material fatigue ageing. This is a process that degrades the electrical, chemical and mechanical properties of a cell. It leads to either a modification of the cell’s structural properties, a variation of the electrolyte composition, a loss of active material or a combination of these three effects, resulting in reduced performance of the cell compared to the its nominal performance (Barré et al., 2013). The ageing mechanisms are different at the cathode and anode (Vetter et al., 2005) and typically more significant at the latter. These can be classified in two macro-categories, i.e. Loss of Lithium Inventory (LLI) and Loss of Active Material (LAM), as per (Birkl et al., 2017). More in detail, they include:

                              (1)


                                 Decomposition of the electrolyte: it causes a loss of Li and a rise in internal resistance, and is enhanced by high temperatures and a high state of charge (SoC);


                              (2)


                                 Cracking formation from solvent co-intercalation and gas evolution: it causes a loss of Li and the exfoliation of the graphite anode, and is enhanced by overcharge;


                              (3)


                                 Decrease of accessible surface and porosity due to continuous solid electrolyte interface (SEI) growth: it causes a rise of the internal resistance and is enhanced by high temperatures, high SoC and high cycling rate;


                              (4)


                                 Volume changes: it causes the loss of active material, and is enhanced by a high cycling rate and high depth of discharge (DoD);


                              (5)


                                 Decomposition of the binder: it causes a loss of cyclable Li and loss of mechanical strength and is enhanced by high SoC and high temperatures;


                              (6)


                                 Corrosion and metallic Li-plating: it causes a loss of cyclable Li, a rise in internal resistance and possible unbalanced potential between cells. High SoC enhances it, together with over charge, low temperatures, high cycling rates and geometric imperfections of the cell.

Sections from Sections 3.1–3.4 present the results of the urban mobility analyses, the capacity fade predictions, the EoL estimates and the comparison between modelled and measured capacity fade of traction batteries. They are based on a set of assumptions, linked to the performance-based nature of the capacity fade models adopted in this work (see Section 2.2), and to their needed modifications to make them compatible with the driving data structure of TEMA (see Section 2.3). Thus, the results must be read by considering this set of assumptions, which inevitably pose some limitations. These are:

                              •

The calendar and cycle capacity fade models presented from Sections 2.2.1–2.2.4 are derived from works of different authors and based on different cell-level test campaign. Hence, their field of applicability could slightly differ, and they are not representative of all possible chemical variants of Li-ion cells available today and in the next few years;


                              •

The set of assumptions needed to scale up the models from cell-to-vehicle level simplifies the electric and thermal dynamics that occur in the battery packs and could be influenced and controlled by the BMS algorithms, which are not considered here. Furthermore Eq. (17) assumes the contributions of the calendar and cycle models purely additive, at the net of a reserve value of 25% for PHEV-1 and 15% for BEV-1 and BEV-2;


                              •

The three battery electric architectures presented in Section 2.4 (2P-96S, 48P-2P-2S and 16S-72P-6S) are representative of three examples derived from market available vehicles and could not resemble all the possible arrangements. Nevertheless, the benefit of adopting the 16S-72P-6S are evident compared to the other two;


                              •

The driving dataset assumed for this work (province of Modena, Italy, 16,263 vehicles), might not be representative for all regions of the world; similarly, the ambient temperature, which influences the battery temperature in parking phases and thus calendar ageing, is not representative of all possible environmental conditions in which electric vehicle might operate;


                              •


                                 Tables 8 and 9 presents some combinations of Li-ion chemistries, vehicles, and recharge strategies which might be unlikely to happen, e.g. a vehicle as BEV-1 is unlikely to be always charged in DC fast charge (recharge strategy 2), as well as a vehicle as BEV-2 is unlikely to be driven below 500 km/month. Nevertheless, it is useful that the scenarios provide the widest possible angle on different use-cases;


                              •

The vehicle-level validation work presented in section 3.4 compares UBE measurements with model’s predictions. This comparison is made despite test vehicles #1 and #2 have a slight different cell chemistry with respect to the model adopted and that the UBE baseline is different from the model’s baseline, being that the “run-in” part not considered in the measurements. It must be also considered that the Cordoba-Arenas et Al. cycle fade model uses average battery temperature as input while the measurements are averaged throughout each driving and charging event, thus reducing the effect of extreme temperatures and that the model predictions made at checkpoints #x.7, #x.9 and #x.11 (Ah-throughput at cell level above 20,000 Ah) might fall in a range beyond the applicability of the model.
